Text Mining and Sentiment Analysis

Shaobo Li

  • Basic text mining with tm package.
  • Sentiment analysis
  • Exercise – Trump Twitter data

We use ABC news data at Kaggle to demonstrate text mining and sentiment analysis. There are many good online tutorials and blogs for text mining in R. One of the best textbooks to read is Text Mining with R, which comprehensively illustrates the package tidytext, which is a tidy approach for text mining.

Load ABC News data

library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)

abcnews <- read_csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/wucdr914q9kzyd7/abcnews-date-text.csv?dl=1")

Basic text mining with tm package.

Corpus

Make text data as Corpus

Corpus is a collection of text documents, but we only have one. R package tm works only with Corpus.

library(tm) 
text<- Corpus(VectorSource(abcnews$headline_text))

standard cleaning

Typically, we should do some standard cleaning, such as converting everything to lower cases, removing punctuations, and removing words that have no values for the analysis (the so-called “stop words”). Let’s look at what are the existing stop words.

# some cleaning
text<- tm_map(text, content_transformer(tolower))
text<- tm_map(text, removePunctuation)
text<- tm_map(text, removeWords, stopwords("english"))

If you ever want to convert Corpus back to data frame, you may use the lines below. To make word cloud, we don’t necessarily need this.

text.df <- data.frame(text=sapply(text, identity), stringsAsFactors=F)

Document matrix

For other text analysis and management, it may be useful to build a term-document matrix. This matrix has the form that row names are each different words and column names are simply the document, which is the news headline. You can conver a document matrix to R matrix using as.matrix(). This will be a very sparse matrix, and should be very large. We are not able to make it for this data (over 700 GB).

dtm <- TermDocumentMatrix(text)
# as.matrix(dtm)

Word Cloud

Word cloud is a very good data visualization tool for text data. It gives you an overall impression that what a set of documents talk about. It is also a very useful figure for presentation. In R, it is easy to generate the word cloud figure using wordcloud package.

library(wordcloud)  
## Warning: package 'wordcloud' was built under R version 3.6.3
wordcloud(text, max.words = 100, random.order = FALSE, rot.per=0.3, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

  • max.words and min.freq: These parameters are used to limit the number of words plotted. max.words will plot the specified number of words and discard least frequent terms, whereas, min.freq will discard all terms whose frequency is below the specified value.
  • random.order: By setting this to FALSE, we make it so that the words with the highest frequency are plotted first. If we don’t set this, it will plot the words in a random order, and the highest frequency words may not necessarily appear in the center.
  • rot.per: This value determines the fraction of words that are plotted vertically.
  • colors: The default value is black. If you want to use different colors based on frequency, you can specify a vector of colors, or use one of the pre-defined color palettes. You can find a list here.

Sentiment analysis

Sentiment data

We will use a tidy approach based on package tidytext to conduct sentiment analysis.

First, there is a important dataset called sentiments in this package. This dataset is essentially pre-built sentiment dictionary. Let’s take a look.

## # A tibble: 2 x 2

## 1 negative   4781

In addition, there are other lexicons contributed by different authors. We can pull these lexicons with get_sentiments(), but you need to install a package textdata first, and then it will ask you if you want to download the specific lexicon.

get_sentiments("bing")  # this is the same as pre-built data "sentiments"
get_sentiments("nrc")
get_sentiments("afinn")

Different lexicon has different sentiment labels. nrc is probably the richest one that has 10 different labels, and a word may have multiple sentiment labels.

Sentiment analysis with inner join

Restructure the data

The first step is to restructure the data. In other words, we need to split sentences to every single word.

abcnews1<- abcnews %>% unnest_tokens(word, headline_text)

Overall sentiment with “nrc” lexicon

In order to know the sentiment category of our document data, we need to join it with the sentiment dataset we saw before. Inner join is commonly used for the joining.

# look at the words belong to "joy" from the sentiment data with nrc lexicon
nrc_joy <- get_sentiments("nrc") %>% 
  filter(sentiment == "joy")
nrc_joy

abcnews1 %>%
  inner_join(nrc_joy) %>%

Sentiment analysis by year

We first restructure our data with daily level, where we count the positive and negative sentiment for all news everyday. In the end, we create the column “year” so that we can further look at the sentiment for each year.

# I recommend you to run these part step by step to see what each line does
abcnews_sentiment_year <- abcnews1 %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  count(publish_date, sentiment) %>%
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative) %>%
  mutate(year= substr(publish_date, 1, 4)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%  # these three lines create an index column for each year.
  mutate(index=row_number(year)) %>%
  ungroup()
abcnews_sentiment_year
## # A tibble: 5,422 x 6
##    publish_date negative positive sentiment year  index

Now we can use ggplot to get the sentiment plot, so we can better observe how ABC News’ emotion is.

ggplot(abcnews_sentiment_year, aes(index, sentiment, fill = year)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~year, ncol = 3, scales = "free_x")

Exercise – Trump Twitter data

You can use the code below to import the data. The data is also available on Blackboard. You may also get the latest version with the most recent tweets at http://www.trumptwitterarchive.com/archive.

trumptwitter<- read_csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/j0n9gu8mncmpocl/TrumpTwitter.csv?dl=1")
trumptwitter
## # A tibble: 46,608 x 7
##    source  text       created_at retweet_count favorite_count is_retweet  id_str
##    <chr>   <chr>      <chr>              <dbl>          <dbl> <lgl>        <dbl>
##  1 Twitte~ "RT @real~ 3/19/2020~         42992              0 TRUE       1.24e18
##  2 Twitte~ "https://~ 3/19/2020~         10226          42405 FALSE      1.24e18
##  3 Twitte~ "RT @FLOT~ 3/19/2020~         27302              0 TRUE       1.24e18
##  4 Twitte~ "America\~ 3/19/2020~         14988          59063 FALSE      1.24e18
##  5 Twitte~ "THANK YO~ 3/19/2020~         27241         140847 FALSE      1.24e18
##  6 Twitte~ "THANK YO~ 3/19/2020~         13910          58791 FALSE      1.24e18
##  7 Twitte~ "RT @Whit~ 3/19/2020~          6627              0 TRUE       1.24e18
##  8 Twitte~ "RT @Surg~ 3/19/2020~          5183              0 TRUE       1.24e18
##  9 Twitte~ "RT @Whit~ 3/19/2020~          9444              0 TRUE       1.24e18
## 10 Twitte~ "RT @Whit~ 3/19/2020~          6304              0 TRUE       1.24e18
## # ... with 46,598 more rows
# convert to Corpus
text<- Corpus(VectorSource(trumptwitter$text))
# basic cleaning
#text<- str_replace_all(text,"[^[:graph:]]", " ")
text<- tm_map(text, function(x) iconv(enc2utf8(x), sub = "byte"))
text<- tm_map(text, content_transformer(tolower))
text<- tm_map(text, removePunctuation)
text<- tm_map(text, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
# word cloud
wordcloud(text, max.words = 100, random.order = FALSE, rot.per=0.3, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

# sentiment analysis
trumptwitter1<- trumptwitter %>% unnest_tokens(word, text)
trumptwitter1

# overall sentiment 
trumptwitter_sentiment_all<- trumptwitter1 %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
  count(sentiment, sort = TRUE)
trumptwitter_sentiment_all

ggplot(trumptwitter_sentiment_all) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(x=reorder(sentiment,n), y=n), fill="blue")+
  labs(x="Sentiment", y="Count")+
  coord_flip()

# overall sentiment by presidential election period
trumptwitter_sentiment_3period<- trumptwitter1 %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
  separate(created_at, into = c("date", "time"), sep=" ") %>%
  separate(date, into = c("month", "day", "year"), sep = "/", remove = F)%>%
  filter(!is.na(year)) %>%
  mutate(year=as.numeric(year), stage=cut(year, breaks = c(-Inf, 2014, 2016, Inf), include.lowest = T, labels = c("Before", "Campaign", "After")))%>%
  group_by(stage, sentiment)%>%
  summarise(n=n())
trumptwitter_sentiment_3period

ggplot(trumptwitter_sentiment_3period) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(x=stage, y=n, fill=sentiment), position = "dodge")+
  labs(x="Election stage", y="Count")


# sentiment by hour
trumptwitter_sentiment <- trumptwitter1 %>%
  separate(created_at, into = c("date", "time"), sep=" ") %>%
  separate(date, into = c("month", "day", "year"), sep = "/", remove = F)%>%
  separate(time, into = c("hour", "second"), sep=":") %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"))

trumptwitter_sentiment1 <- trumptwitter_sentiment %>%
  mutate(year=as.numeric(year), stage=cut(year, breaks = c(-Inf, 2014, 2016, Inf), include.lowest = T, labels = c("Before", "Campaign", "After")))%>%
  filter(!is.na(year)) %>%
  group_by(stage, hour, sentiment)%>%
  summarise(n=n())%>%
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative) %>%
  ungroup()

ggplot(trumptwitter_sentiment1) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(x=as.numeric(hour), y=sentiment), fill="blue")+
  labs(x="Hour during a day", y="Score")+
  facet_wrap(~stage, nrow = 3, scales = "free_x")
